#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:3
msgid "Accessing Files Quick Reference"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:5
msgid ""
"For development of modules to use in Pyodide, the best experience comes from "
"using Pyodide in Node and mounting the development directory into Pyodide "
"using the NodeFS. In the NodeFS, all changes to your native file system are "
"immediately reflected in Pyodide and vice versa."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:10
msgid ""
"If your code is browser-only, you can use the Chrome `NativeFS` for "
"development. This will not automatically sync up with your native file "
"system, but it is still quite convenient."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:14
msgid "In Node.js"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:16
msgid ""
"It's recommended to use {js:func}`pyodide.mountNodeFS` to mount the host "
"file system so that it is accessible from inside of Pyodide. For example if "
"you have a Python package in a folder called `my_package`, you can do:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:20
msgid ""
"pyodide.mountNodeFS(\"my_package\", \"/path/to/my_package\");\n"
"pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"import my_package\n"
"# ... use it\n"
"`);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:28
msgid "In the browser"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:30
msgid ""
"To access local files in Chrome, you can use the File System Access API to "
"acquire a directory handle and then mount the directory into the Pyodide "
"file system with {js:func}`pyodide.mountNativeFS`. To acquire the directory "
"handle, you have to fill out a folder picker the first time. The handle can "
"subsequently be stored in the `IndexedDB`. You will still be prompted for "
"read and write access, but you don't have to deal with the folder picker "
"again."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:37
msgid "The following code is a good starting point:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:39
msgid ""
"const { get, set } = await import(\n"
"  \"https://unpkg.com/idb-keyval@5.0.2/dist/esm/index.js\"\n"
");\n"
"\n"
"/**\n"
" * Mount a folder from your native filesystem as the directory\n"
" * `pyodideDirectory`. If `directoryKey` was used previously, then it will "
"reuse\n"
" * the same folder as last time. Otherwise, it will show a directory "
"picker.\n"
" */\n"
"async function mountDirectory(pyodideDirectory, directoryKey) {\n"
"  let directoryHandle = await get(directoryKey);\n"
"  const opts = {\n"
"    id: \"mountdirid\",\n"
"    mode: \"readwrite\",\n"
"  };\n"
"  if (!directoryHandle) {\n"
"    directoryHandle = await showDirectoryPicker(opts);\n"
"    await set(directoryKey, directoryHandle);\n"
"  }\n"
"  const permissionStatus = await directoryHandle.requestPermission(opts);\n"
"  if (permissionStatus !== \"granted\") {\n"
"    throw new Error(\"readwrite access to directory not granted\");\n"
"  }\n"
"  const { syncfs } = await pyodide.mountNativeFS(\n"
"    pyodideDirectory,\n"
"    directoryHandle,\n"
"  );\n"
"  return syncfs;\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:71
msgid "See {ref}`nativefs-api` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:73
msgid "Downloading external archives"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:75
msgid ""
"If you are using Pyodide in the browser, you should download external files "
"and save them to the virtual file system. The recommended way to do this is "
"to zip the files and unpack them into the file system with {js:func}`pyodide."
"unpackArchive`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:80
msgid ""
"let zipResponse = await fetch(\"myfiles.zip\");\n"
"let zipBinary = await zipResponse.arrayBuffer();\n"
"pyodide.unpackArchive(zipBinary, \"zip\");\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:86
msgid ""
"You can also download the files from Python using {py:func}`~pyodide.http."
"pyfetch`, which is a convenient wrapper of JavaScript {js:func}`fetch`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/accessing-files.md:90
msgid ""
"await pyodide.runPythonAsync(`\n"
"  from pyodide.http import pyfetch\n"
"  response = await pyfetch(\"https://some_url/myfiles.zip\")\n"
"  await response.unpack_archive()\n"
"`)\n"
msgstr ""
